  "summary": "Detective Spence, Inspector Grieve, and Rolly Claude discuss the investigation into the death of the man known as Enoch Yates. Rolly notes that the deceased was the only lead to finding André, making the search difficult. Spence suggests that media coverage might prompt André to emerge. After Rolly departs, Spence examines an expensive gold lighter marked with the initials \"D.H.\" and instructs Grieve to trace it through Bond Street shops.\n\nThe investigation focuses on a broken watch found at the scene, which indicates the time 9:10. While Grieve suggests this marks the time of the crime, Spence expresses skepticism, noting that criminals sometimes smash watches to create false alibis. Forensic evidence places the time of death between 8:00 PM and 11:00 PM. Additionally, Chief Inspector Graves reports that a gardener named Edwards saw David Hunter exiting a side door at Flambrook at approximately 7:30 PM, contradicting the belief that Hunter was in London. Spence also considers an unknown lipstick found under a wardrobe in the Stagg hotel, noting the room had been vacant for three weeks.\n\nSpence visits an elegant building near Shepherd's Market to investigate. After speaking with a uniformed staff member, Spence learns that both Mrs. Gordon Claude and David Hunter have been staying there since the previous Saturday. The staff member confirms they were both present the previous night and suggests checking room service records for breakfast deliveries. Spence proceeds to the fourth floor and visits apartment nine, where David Hunter admits him to the residence. There, Spence meets Rosaline Claude, who appears tense.",
